:: path-vimrc
I’ve clutched my .vimrc. It’s a pathetic sight—like a drowning man holding onto a single, gold-plated anchor. My 2011 MacBook Pro groans as I toggle a fold. The fans hit 6,000 RPM. It’s the sound of a man refusing to admit that the world has moved on to VS Code and Copilot.

My boss's face does that twitchy thing that happens right before a Performance Improvement Plan is issued. He’s looking at my terminal, where a Ruby 1.9.3 process is hanging on a broken pipe. 

I see the Apple Watch on his wrist flare up again: another 🚀 reaction. The vibration against his skin must be constant, a rhythmic reminder that he’s winning and I’m just a legacy dependency.

"Devin," Greg whispers, his voice thick with the fake empathy of a corporate executioner. "The board doesn't want 'artisanal logic.' They want *velocity*. They want the kind of scale that doesn't rely on a man who still thinks `attr_accessible` is a valid security strategy."

I stare at his hairline until he feels the weight of his own mortality. I could explain why the Asset Pipeline is superior to whatever Webpack-adjacent hellscape he's been pitched this week, but it would be like explaining the internal combustion engine to a man who only wants to talk about 'teleportation.'

[[A) "I can automate the quarterly reviews with a shell script. It'll be beautiful."->prologue-walk-home]]
[[B) Stare at him until the silence becomes a HR violation.->prologue-walk-home]]

:: path-rust
I spend forty-eight hours fighting the borrow checker. It’s like wrestling an angel that keeps telling me that my memory management is "unethical." My 2011 MacBook is so hot I could fry an egg on the 'S' key.

I don't finish the system. I don't even finish the boilerplate. But I do manage to make a "Hello World" binary that is memory-safe, thread-safe, and exactly 4MB of pure, unadulterated hubris. 

For a second, I feel it. That old surge of power. I’ve built a foundation so solid it could survive a nuclear winter. I imagine Bob seeing this—him nodding, cleaning his glasses on his tie, and saying, "Clean code is the only true leverage, Devin." I feel untouchable. I feel like a Senior Dev again.

[img[src/images/path-rust-hubris.png]]
<!-- IMAGE PROMPT: A stylized illustration of Devin wrestling a glowing, angelic figure made of binary code (the Borrow Checker) in a dark server room. -->

[[Next->path-rust-part-2]]

:: path-rust-part-2
Monday morning, I show it to Greg. I’m vibrating with the technical purity of it. I’ve already rehearsed the explanation of how zero-cost abstractions will save us millions in compute.

He stares at the terminal. He stares at the `Cargo.lock` file like it's a suicide note written in a language he doesn't speak. My MacBook is still ticking from the heat.

"Where is the AI, Devin?" he asks. His voice is flat. The twitch in his eye has been replaced by a terrifying, absolute stillness. "The board wanted a 10x leverage generator. You gave me a... 'zero-cost abstraction' for a problem we don't have."

"Greg, it's about the foundation—"

"This isn't even 'unscalable chic' anymore. It's just... obsolete."

He doesn't even wait for me to explain the ownership model. He just slides a cardboard box across the desk. It’s already got my spare mechanical keyboard and my "I survived the Cloudflare outage" mug in it. 

I look out the window. Down in the parking lot, Greg’s Audi is backed into my spot with sickening precision. It looks like a polished, metallic predator waiting for its next victim.

**GAME OVER: THE PURIST'S PLIGHT**
*I chose technical excellence over corporate survival. The borrow checker is happy, but my mortgage lender isn't. The Austin Public Library has good Wi-Fi, I hear. And the woods nearby are quiet.*

[[Try again, but this time lie like a professional.->prologue-greg-office]]

:: path-a-grind
I clear the kitchen table. Coffee. Whiteboard markers. A dog-eared copy of -Pattern Recognition and Machine Learning- that I've been pretending to read since 2019. It’s damp, and it smells faintly of the future I’m trying to avoid.

The hours blur. Eigenvectors. Backpropagation. I drink so much coffee my hands start to look like they'd shake during a drug test. My 2011 MacBook struggles to render the LaTeX in the PDFs. It’s a 200-level math problem being solved by a man with a 100-level grip on reality.

By 4am I'm staring at a whiteboard covered in notation that could qualify as abstract art. Or a map of a campsite.

Monday arrives like a freight train with no brakes.

[["Go to the meeting."|episode-2-monday]]

:: path-b-liquidate
I open eBay. The IBM Model M fetches $140 from a collector in Berlin. The shirt — size Large, never washed, mint condition irony — goes for $43 to a Portland startup founder who wasn't alive in 1998. 

I feel the "wrapper" of my life thinning. Each sale is a line removed from my `~/.vimrc`.

It is not enough.

But it buys two weeks of breathing room. Two weeks until I’m "unhosted."

[["Continue."|episode-2-monday]]

:: path-c-create-guy
I sit in the dark for exactly eleven minutes. Then I open a browser. My 2011 MacBook Pro fans kick in just opening LinkedIn. The modern web is a bloated corpse, and I’m about to perform a digital autopsy.

First: LinkedIn. I create a profile. "Kieran Voss — AI Solutions Architect. Ex-DeepMind. Current: Independent LLM Consultant (Fortune 500 Focus)." Headshot: generated. Employee count at his fictional "Kairos AI Advisory" firm: three. All of them Kieran.

Then the CV. I write it in the language of snakes. "Orchestrated multi-agent LLM pipelines at scale." "Reduced token overhead by 47% through deterministic sampling strategies." It sounds like it means something. It might mean nothing. Greg won't know the difference. He thinks 'deterministic' is a type of coffee.

I hit save. I’ve just deployed a monolith of lies.

[["Continue."|episode-2-monday]]
